wr_Wordlist1_StrategyReport:
I tried to picture it as a scene: a needle travelling through an island which had a pool. palace. a bird with teeth next to a sister. then tried to imagine the pool as a scene of a crime with a blood and boot. And there's sweat and you should shower before getting in a pool in case you're sweaty.
And now I realise I forgot pocket... 
To be honest with you I only know about this technique because I administer the CVLT-II as part of my job and have read in the literature about this technique of making the list items into a story.
wr_Wordlist2_StrategyReport:
I tried to recognise the ones I forgot from the previous task. then tried to remember my 'story' with the needle on the street of the island. showering at the pool. the boot and the blood crime scene thing.

wr_Wordlist1_StrategyReport: I tried to visualise the words and create a story surrounding each word in the order they came up. wr_Wordlist2_StrategyReport: I didn't manage to do the same as the previous task (creating mental images of the words) because I had already created a mental image of the order the words were in before and it was therefore more difficult to override that with new images. Therefore when I was recalling the words it was easier to try and remember the original images I created in the first study. but I was less accurate and couldn't remember as many because it was a longer time between learning and recalling the words.
wr_Wordlist3_StrategyReport: I did the same as the first task - this time I didn't try to create a new set of images for the new order of words. I just tried to fit the words back into the mental image that I created in the first task. It also made my recall better because the images were fresh in my mind and I had now seen them 3 times

WR_Wordlist1_StrategyReport: I tried to visualise the words and create a story surrounding each word in the order they came up. For example, the first word was pool so I visualised a swimming pool, the second word was flower so I imagined a flower floating on the surface of the pool. This helped me to link the two words together in my mind so I remembered both of them and made it easy to recall because I had created an image that I could easily remember.
WR_Wordlist2_StrategyReport: I didn't manage to do the same as the previous task (creating mental images of the words) because I had already created a mental image of the order the words were in before and it was therefore more difficult to override that with new images. Therefore when I was recalling the words it was easier to try and remember the original images I created in the first study, but I was less accurate and couldn't remember as many because it was a longer time between learning and recalling the words.
WR_Wordlist3_StrategyReport: I did the same as the first task - this time I didn't try to create a new set of images for the new order of words, I just tried to fit the words back into the mental image that I created in the first task. This worked better as the images were already in my mind and therefore they were reinforced by looking at the words again in this context. It also made my recall better because the images were fresh in my mind and I had now seen them 3 times
ILL_strategyuse_desc: I tried to visualise doing the tasks and that helped me to remember most of them. I also tried to think of what I would need to do if I was returning from the grocery store and most of the tasks made sense in that context which helped.
